reviewBlob: A rather disappointing beer. An amber color, nice head, decent nose of hops and slight malts. Mouthfeel fairly medicore, and the taste of hops and malt were promient but not quite strong enough for my liking. A better alternative than other bitters or browns.
Limited smell and flavor like any old cheap beer. Watery mouthfeel with a cereal grain taste. Very pale yellow body, weak head. Good for a cheap buzz but nothing more.

Malty aroma, smooth but with a very slight richness in the flavor. Pours a pale golden. As far as Canadian lagers availabe in MI, it's a better staple than Labatt's but lacks the richness of Molson Canadian.
Aroma limited to faintest smell of grain. Mouthfeel and appearance similar to the many macros on the market. Miller's answer to Bud's sweeter flavor, but not quite as sweet.

The best word to describe this beer is creamy... creamy pour, creamy head, and creamy mouthfeel... more than hints of mocha and bitterness. Good on special nights but the rule of too much of a good thing applies with this beer. A little to specific for a staple beer, but deliscious the same
On tap... limited mouthfeel, pale golden color, aroma of wheat and vanilla, smooth taste of malt with a hint of sweetness. Not as good as Oberon but damn good.
Smooth and decent taste but limited mouthfeel and not quite the taste for me.
Delicious and creamy; thick mouthfeel, wonderful companion to a thick steak
Black appearance.Mouthfeel rather thin. Roasted flavors rather subtle, for a stout. Flavor lacks complexity of Bells or the hoppiness of Guinness ES. A decent dark beer but a medicore stout.
Very interesting beer from MI... the pine smell has a soapy(?) fruity smell with a similar taste. Unique hop flavors. Not the best but worth giving a try.

Finally a pleasant surprise in the world of wheat. taste of banana and vanilla, and a cloudy body. No damn honey or cough syrup fruit in taste or smell. Bells is Better. (my new slogan to everything, maybe theyll start paying me.)
heh... another one... American beer, ya get what ya pay for.
If you want a summer wheat brew drink Oberon from Bells. More flavor. Still its a Sammys.
Drank a case of this as a joke. It didnt even know it alcohol in it... like being shocked by the advent of the picture box and talkies.

I have to re-rate this after so more sampling in this style. Not enough hops for my liking (probably spoiled by Bells) and no malt flavoring to compliment the taste. Still a decent brew but there are better.
Dark brown body, good head retension, thick mouthfeel with plenty of roasted flavor. A good porter, although not a favorite.
The better of three most common PAs in my neck of the woods (Bass, this, and Sammy). A little darker body with a more complex malt flavoring to compliment the strong hops.
An ale from Sammy. Certainly not their best. Weak flavoring and little aroma.
An average ale. Couldnt see anything to rate it over any of Sammy Adams ales.
The better light beer because it has more alcohol. If youre already drinking this, its giving you exactly what you want. Nothing out of the ordinary.
Like Natural Light... its a better light beer with exactly what you need if youre drinking light beer.
A better light beer. Nothing special, just cereal grain malt with enough hops to balance.
The weakest of the standard Miller beers. Lite Ice gives you more of what youre looking for in this can.
A no-frills beer: cheap with decent cereal grain flavor, and plenty of alcohol. A beer to drink just cause ya wanna drink.

Ever notice how sub-premiums seem to taste better? They exactly whats expected of them: a nice malt flavor consisting of cereal grain with little hops. Good for what its for, cheap and better than most others.

I know this is an attempt at better beer, but Id rather drink Bud or Miller.
"Hmmm... add more hops to swill, make good beer." The taste is just too off-putting, must drink ice cold.
Decent American Standard brew. On par with their Canadian. Good beer to buy instead of Domestic. Support the Canuks.
Not even an attempt at malt flavoring.

brewerName: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
reviewBlob: One of the best tasting dark lagers available. Actually has flavor to match the name unlike Heines or Becks. Creamy mocha flavoring in a smooth drinking beer.

Q. When is the best time to drink light beer?
A. When its free.
B. When its cheap.
C. When its all there is.
D. All of the above.
Like most macros, its drinkable and, you know, the hot summers and... yadda yadda. Better of the macros.
If its free, then its good. Average run of the mill American macro only with less flavor, less alcohol, and less calories. Hooray, Ill have another Whopper.
Dark brown body, pours with a decent head. Chocolate taste with decent bitter finish. Enjoy the Kalamazoo stout better but another fine Bells product.
Better than regular Bud.
The hops in this Bells smack you right in the taste buds. Acidic citrus flavor with balanced malt flavor. Damn good Bells and best Pale Ale yet.
Premium American breweries try too hard at making nothing... just give us some malted cereal grains and alcohol. Too much rice flavor for my taste. If it aint free, give me a no-frills Busch.
As a person familiar with American swill, the aroma and flavor of this beer was pure heaven. It is everything Im looking for in a Pilsner.
Nice golden appearance with some cloudiness. Tangy vannila and citrus flavor. The perfect mouthfeel and flavor for a summers eve.
Sweet, fruity aroma that follows through in the taste. A strong fruit-malt beginning complimented with a pleasant bitter finish.
As a lager it out performs wonderfully: thick mouthfeel, great taste and flavor. Sets the Sammy Adams standard.
Looks and smells similar to the Boston Lager with a taste of spice to make this a wonderful addition to my regular Sammys drink list.
The only good light beer is a free light beer.

If you want "malt pop" or "beer soup" why spend money for premium ultra-filtered watered down beer when you can buy this. Wonderful after hard labor, hot days, or late night bull sessions. Puts a taste of ferment cereal grains in your mouth. Cheers!
First try at a lambic. Decent appearance, taste, and aroma. Similar to peach champagne with a malt undertones. Not bad but nothing Id drink regularly.
Very sweet beginning but a very sour finish, like an overly ripe fruit juice with malt. I may have bought a bad bottle.
I thought beer-pop was a phrase used for American beers. Not enough flavor for such a high price.
A fairly average beer in both taste and aroma. Far better than most, but representst the least that Bells can offer. Try any other of products.
Okay but not great. try the Canadian
A better brew than their Ice, a decent macro lager, better than the Americans
A decent but average beer, although the aftertaste gets old after too many
